   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Selecting and Filtering - Lecture"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "039146d4-adde-4b18-85cc-6cef8cecc7ba",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The filter function\n",
    "\n",
    "You should already be familiar with the filter function\n",
    "-> filter(predicate, iterable)\n",
    "-> returns all elements of iterable where predicate(element) is True\n",
    "\n",
    "predicate can be None - in which case it is the identity function\n",
    "f(x) -> x\n",
    "-> in other words thruthy elements will only be retained\n",
    "-> filter returns a lazy iterator\n",
    "\n",
    "We can achieve the same result using generator expressions\n",
    "\n",
    "predicate is not None\n",
    "(item for item in iterable if pred(item))\n",
    "predicate is None\n",
    "(item for item in iterable if item)\n",
    "(item for item in iterable if bool(item))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "1e27d09a-4c23-45c6-b902-fe62c9fbedd8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Example\n",
    "\n",
    "filter(lambda x: x < 4, [1, 10, 2, 10, 3, 10]) -> 1, 2, 3\n",
    "filter(None, [0, '', 'hello', 100, False]) -> 'hello', 100\n",
    "\n",
    "-> remember that filter returns a lazy iterator"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "51409f88-ec99-4f11-99ef-64ad39f16ae3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "itertools.filterfalse\n",
    "\n",
    "This works the same way as filter function\n",
    "But instead of retaining elements where the predicate evaluates to True\n",
    "It retains elements where the predicate evaluates to False\n",
    "\n",
    "Example\n",
    "\n",
    "filterfalse(lambda x: < 4, [1, 10, 2, 10, 3, 10]) -> 10, 10, 10\n",
    "filter(None, [0, '', 'hello', 100, False]) -> 0, '', False\n",
    "\n",
    "-> Filterfalse is a lazy iterator"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "665bea78-608b-4ba8-a352-64f8bc2d2eec",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "itertools.compress\n",
    "\n",
    "No this is not a compressor in the sense of a zip archive\n",
    "It is basically a way of filtering one iterable using the truthiness of items in another iterable\n",
    "\n",
    "data =      ['a',   'b', 'c', 'd', 'e']\n",
    "selectors = [True, False, 1,   0]  None\n",
    "\n",
    "compress(data, selectors) -> a, c\n",
    "\n",
    "-> compress returns a lazy iterator"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "ed26ccc0-df37-4965-859d-7aaa294beda1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "itertools.takewhile\n",
    "\n",
    "takewhile(pred, iterable)\n",
    "\n",
    "The takewhile function returns an iterator that will yield items while pred(items) is Truthy\n",
    "-> at that point the iterator is exhausted, even if there are more items in iterable whose predicate would be truthy\n",
    "\n",
    "takewhile(lamdba x: x < 5, [1, 3, 5, 2, 1]) -> 1, 3\n",
    "\n",
    "-> takewhile is a lazy iterator"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "cf039fb8-dd29-4a44-b99c-984ded7600c8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "itertools.dropwhile\n",
    "\n",
    "dropwhile(pred, iterable)\n",
    "\n",
    "The dropwhile function returns an iterator that will start iterating (and yield all remaining elements) once pred(item) becomes Falsy\n",
    "\n",
    "dropwhile(lambda x: x < 5, [1, 3, 5, 2, 1]) -> 5, 2, 1\n",
    "\n",
    "-> dropwhile is a lazy iterator"
   ]
  },
